a countable fundamental system of entourages (hence in particular a uniformity defined by a countable family of pseudometrics) can be defined by a single pseudometric. A consequence is that \"any\" uniform structure can be defined as above by a (possibly uncountable) family of pseudometrics (see Bourbaki: General Topology Chapter IX \u00a71 no. 4).\nUniform cover definition.\nA uniform space formula_95 is a set formula_42 equipped with a distinguished family of coverings formula_97 called \"uniform covers\", drawn from the set of coverings of formula_91 that form a when ordered by star refinement. One says that a cover formula_99 is a \"star refinement\" of cover formula_100 written formula_101 if for every formula_102 there is a formula_103 such that if formula_104 then formula_105 Axiomatically, the condition of being a filter reduces to:\nGiven a point formula_38 and a uniform cover formula_119 one can consider the union of the members of formula_99 that contain formula_38 as a typical neighbourhood of formula_38 of \"size\" formula_119 and this intuitive measure applies uniformly over the space.\nGiven a uniform space in the entourage sense, define a cover formula_99 to be uniform if there is some entourage formula_19 such that for each formula_126 there is an formula_127 such that formula_128 These uniform covers form a uniform space as in the second definition. Conversely, given a uniform space in the uniform cover sense, the supersets of formula_129 as formula_99 ranges over the uniform covers, are the entourages for a uniform space as in the first definition. Moreover, these two transformations are inverses of each other. \nTopology of uniform spaces.\nEvery uniform space formula_42 becomes a topological space by defining a nonempty subset formula_132 to be open if and only if for every formula_133 there exists an entourage formula_17 such that formula_135 is a subset of formula_136 In this topology, the neighbourhood filter of a point formula_38 is formula_