f complete regularity: for any formula_155 and a neighbourhood formula_42 of formula_157 there is a continuous real-valued function formula_150 with formula_159 and equal to 1 in the complement of formula_160\nIn particular, a compact Hausdorff space is uniformizable. In fact, for a compact Hausdorff space formula_42 the set of all neighbourhoods of the diagonal in formula_2 form the \"unique\" uniformity compatible with the topology.\nA Hausdorff uniform space is metrizable if its uniformity can be defined by a \"countable\" family of pseudometrics. Indeed, as discussed above, such a uniformity can be defined by a \"single\" pseudometric, which is necessarily a metric if the space is Hausdorff. In particular, if the topology of a vector space is Hausdorff and definable by a countable family of seminorms, it is metrizable.\nUniform continuity.\nSimilar to continuous functions between topological spaces, which preserve topological properties, are the uniformly continuous functions between uniform spaces, which preserve uniform properties. \nA uniformly continuous function is defined as one where inverse images of entourages are again entourages, or equivalently, one where the inverse images of uniform covers are again uniform covers. Explicitly, a function formula_163 between uniform spaces is called if for every entourage formula_17 in formula_165 there exists an entourage formula_19 in formula_42 such that if formula_168 then formula_169 or in other words, whenever formula_17 is an entourage in formula_165 then formula_172 is an entourage in formula_42, where formula_174 is defined by formula_175\nAll uniformly continuous functions are continuous with respect to the induced topologies. \nUniform spaces with uniform maps form a category. An isomorphism between uniform spaces is called a &lt;templatestyles src=\"Template:Visible anchor/styles.css\" /&gt;uniform isomorphism; explicitly, it is a uniformly continuous bijection whose inverse is also uniformly continuous. \nA is an injective uniformly continuous map formula_176 between uniform spaces whose inverse formula_177 is also uniformly continuous, where the image formula_178 has the subspace uniformity inherited from formula_179\nCompleteness.\nGeneralizing the notion of complete metric space, one can also define completeness for uniform spaces. Instead of working with Cauchy sequences, one works with Cauchy filters (or Cauchy nets).\nA (respectively, a ) on a uniform space formula_42 is a filter (respectively, a prefilter) formula_181 such that for every entourage formula_182 there exists formula_183 with formula_184 In other words, a filter is Cauchy if it contains \"arbitrarily small\" sets. It follows from the definitions that each filter that converges (with respect to the topology defined by the uniform structure) is a Cauchy filter.\nA is a Cauchy filter that does not contain any smaller (that is, coarser) Cauchy filter (other than itself). It can be shown that every Cauchy filter contains a unique minimal Cauchy filter. The neighbourhood filter of each point (the filter consisting of all neighbourhoods of the point) is a minimal Cauchy filter.\nConversely, a uniform space is called if every Cauchy filter converges. Any compact Hausdorff space is a complete uniform space with respect to the unique uniformity compatible with the topology.\nComplete uniform spaces enjoy the following important property: if formula_185 is a \"uniformly continuous\" function from a \"dense\" subset formula_41 of a uniform space formula_42 into a \"complete\" uniform space formula_188 then formula_150 can be extended (uniquely) into a uniformly continuous function on all of formula_72\nA topological space that can be made into a complete uniform space, whose uniformity induces the original topology, is called a completely uniformizable space.\nA &lt;templatestyles src=\"Template:Visible anchor/styles.css\" /&gt;completion of a uniform space formula_42 is a pair formula_192 consisting of a complete uniform space formula_193 and a uniform embedding formula_194 whose image formula_178 is a dense subset of formula_196 \nHausdorff completion of a uniform space.\nAs with metric spaces, every uniform space formula_42 has a &lt;templatestyles src=\"Template:Visible anchor/styles.css\" /&gt;Hausdorff completion: that is, there exists a complete Hausdorff uniform space formula_165 and a uniformly continuous map formula_176 (if formula_42 is a Hausdorff uniform space then formula_201 is a topological embedding) with the following property:\n for any uniformly continuous mapping formula_150 of formula_42 into a complete Hausdorff uniform space formula_204 there is a unique uniformly continuous map formula_205 such that formula_206\nThe Hausdorff completion formula_165 is unique up to isomorphism. As a set, formula_165 can be taken to consist of the minimal Cauchy filters on formula_72 As the neighbourhood filter formula_210 of each point formula_38 in formula_42 is a minimal Cauchy filter, the map formula_201 can be defined by mapping formula_38 to formula_215 The map formula_201 thus defined is in general not injective; in fact, the graph of the equivalence relation formula_217 is the intersection of all entourages of formula_91 and thus formula_201 is injective precisely when formula_42 is Hausdorff.\nThe uniform structure on formula_165 is defined as follows: for each &lt;templatestyles src=\"Template:Visible anchor/styles.css\" /&gt;\"symmetric\" entourage formula_17 (that is, such that formula_223 implies formula_224), let formula_225 be the set of all pairs formula_226 of minimal Cauchy filters \"which have in common at least one formula_17-small set\". The sets formula_225 can be shown to form a fundamental system of entourages; formula_165 is equipped with the uniform structure thus defined.\nThe set formula_178 is then a dense subset of formula_179 If formula_42 is Hausdorff, then formula_201 is an isomorphism onto formula_234 and thus formula_42 can be